<p><i>Hilye</i> inscribed on the petals of a pink rose symbolising the Prophet (18th century).</p>
</div>
</div>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3> <span class="mw-headline" id="Calligraphic_representations">Calligraphic representations</span></h3>
<p>The most common visual representation of the Prophet in Islamic art, especially in Arabic-speaking areas, is by a calligraphic representation of his name, a sort of <a href="Monogram" title="Monogram">monogram</a> in roughly circular form, often given a decorated frame. Such inscriptions are normally in Arabic, and may rearrange or repeat forms, or add a blessing or honorific, or for example the word "messenger" or a contraction of it. The range of ways of representing Muhammad's name is considerable, including <a href="Ambigram" title="Ambigram">ambigrams</a>; he is also frequently symbolised by a rose.</p>
<p>The more elaborate versions relate to other Islamic traditions of special forms of calligraphy such as those writing the <a href="Names_of_God_in_Islam" title="Names of God in Islam">names of God</a>, and the secular <a href="Tughra" title="Tughra">tughra</a> or elaborate monogram of Ottoman rulers.</p>
<div align="center">
<ul class="gallery">
